This dataset is perfect for marketing analytics which is something Iâm very passionate about exploring. Understanding how certain factors can affect consumer behaviour. Rationale for Dataset Selection

I have chosen the Shopping Behavior Dataset from Kaggle because it offers a multifaceted view of individual consumer transactions, demographics, product details, frequency, and promotions. This dataset is ideal for marketing analytics, which is an area I am passionate about exploring since I am also in the Integrated Marketing Certificate Program. Understanding how certain factors affect consumer behavior is valuable for both academic and practical applications. Additionally, I am currently working on a different dataset for my marketing classes, and I wanted to integrate my interests across both projects.

Data Quality and Complexity Assessment

Dataset Dimensions: 3,900 observations and 18 variables

Categorical Variables (11): Customer ID, Payment Method, Promo Code Used, Discount Applied, Shipping Type, Subscription Status, Season, Color, Size, Location, and Category

Numeric Variables (4): Age, Previous Purchases, Purchase Amount (USD), and Review Rating

Data Completeness Chart

Potential Missingness

Some categorical nulls like Promo Code Used and Discount Applied may represent implicit âNoâ/âNAâ values rather than true missing data. However based on my missingness test, this dataset does not require a lot of tidying because there is no missingness. In addition, high dollar amounts could not register in the dataset since there might be data entry limits with the website, there could be skewness in the data but within my EDA I will explore this further. Upon further research in FigureÂ 1, this graph shows that this dataset is considered complete with no missing values.

Data Quality Notes

This dataset is considered substantially complete despite the presence of âNoâ values in the promo code variable. These missing values can be appropriately handled through standard data cleaning techniques. The variables demonstrate sufficient complexity and diversity for robust data analysis. The dataset contains numerous unique values across categorical variables, and some variables may require string manipulation or reference during analysis. Overall, the dataset is well-suited for exploring relationships between consumer demographics, purchasing behavior, and product preferences, making it an excellent choice for applied marketing analytics.

Univariate Analysis on Purchase Amount

Insights on the Distribution by Purchases

FigureÂ 2 displays the distribution of purchase amounts is fairly uniform, with customers making purchases across the full price range rather than clustering around specific dollar amounts. This suggests the store sells a balanced mix of products at different price points, with no strong tendency toward either low-cost or high-cost purchases that may skew data.

BoxPlot of Purchase Amount

Insight on the Distribution by Purchases (Boxplot)

In FigureÂ 3, data shows that the majority of purchases range from 10 to 100 dollars, 50% of those purchases ranging from 40 to 80 dollars.

Univariate Variate Analysis on Frequency of Items Bought

Insights on the Distribution of Frequency of Items Purchased

Looking at the clothing purchase frequency graph, FigureÂ 4 displays several ideas that stood out to me. Pants, jewelry, and blouses were the most items purchases with around 180-185 each, suggesting these are popular items. The data shows three distinct tiers of popularity, with the top tier items (Pants through Sweater) seeing 170-185 purchases, a middle tier (Jacket through Scarf) ranging from 150-165 purchases, and a lower tier (Hat through Jeans) falling between 125-145 purchases. Accessories were very popular overall with jewelry ranking second and sunglasses, belts, and sandals appearing in the upper-middle range. Footwear categories are distributed throughout the chart suggesting seasonal influences. Jeans ranked last despite being a wardrobe staple, which could reflect market saturation or higher price points that limit repeat purchases. There were no significant outliers that could be important to note.

Age Univariate Analysis on the Distribution of Customer Age

Insights on the Distribution of Customer Age

FigureÂ 5 reveals that customers from age 18 to 73 are shopping consistently and most age groups have about 200 customers. Some dipping lower and some rising higher. The main age ranges are late 20s to mid 30s and mid to late 50s. Overall, the relatively flat distribution across such a wide age range suggests that shopping is consistent and has a wide range of appeal. Further research would help identify precise marketing, pricing, and product recommendations.

Analysis on Color and Size

Insights on Purchase Numbers by Color and Size

FigureÂ 6 explores the relationship between color and size in terms of products sold. Medium size has the majority of purchases per color (60-90), Large, Small and XL underperform and follow in that order with Large being moderately above Small and XL that are seemingly low in number. There is an even distribution across the items colors however in order to increase sales focusing on the highest selling colors could increase revenue. From there, there is insight that colors like Teal, Violet and Olive are the highest selling colors for the highest selling size. Meaning producing more in these colors may be beneficial. In addition, the size disparity between Medium and sizes like Small and XL could be an opportunity for growth that should be tested.

Bivariate Analysis On Clothes & Seasons

Insights on Item Purchases by Season

FigureÂ 7 shows how people shop depending on the season. In the fall, everyone starts buying more boots, jackets, and sweaters as it gets colder. By spring, you can tell people are shifting into warmer weather because things like T-shirts, sneakers, and sunglasses start getting bought more. Summer has a mix of items but winter focuses on the heavy cold-weather clothes like coats and hoodies. Overall, it just shows that people shop based on the weather, cold months prompt the purchase of warmer clothes, warm months prompt the purchase of summer outfits, and accessories stay pretty consistent year-round.

Discount Usage by Payment Method

Proportion of Total Transactions by Payment Method

Insights on Discount Usage by Payment Method and the Proportion of Total Transactions by Payment Method

FigureÂ 8 reveals remarkably consistent discount usage patterns across all payment methods, with approximately 60% of transactions not receiving discounts (red) and 40% receiving discounts (green) regardless of how customers pay. The uniformity across Bank Transfer, Cash, Credit Card, Debit Card, PayPal, and Venmo suggests that discount application is independent of payment method choice in this dataset. Debit Card are more price-sensitive, since they used a higher proportion of discounts (45%). Even though it is clear that it was a slight difference it stands out compared to the rest of the data. We also see that payment method promotions are unlikely to drive results. Discount usage is shown as slightly uniform across payment types and payment method doesnt seem to vary. In FigureÂ 9, we can see that the proportion of different payment usage doesnt necessarily vary. In addition, since 60% of customers purchase without discounts, thereâs room for growth by offering discounts based on purchase frequency since customers would purchase more tend to spend more.

Revenue Across Age Groups by Subscription Status

Insights on Revenue Across Age Groups by Subscription Status

FigureÂ 10 illustrates total revenue distribution across five age groups, segmented by subscription status. Total revenue shows a dramatic upward trend with age. The middle three age groups cluster showing that even though young adults contribute moderately to revenue and 55+ demographic is spending the majority of the money. The 55+ age generates the highest total revenue ($82M) but most notably subscribers in this group contribute more revenue of any other age group. This means that the older population as a whole and older subscribers are more valuable customers. This suggests a change in spending behavior at age 55, possibly related to life circumstances..

According to FigureÂ 11, there doesnât appear to be a strong geographic clustering pattern since high and low activity states are spread across the country. Number of Purchases by Gender

Insights on Purchases by Gender

FigureÂ 13 reveals a significant gender imbalance in the shopping dataset. Males made approximately 68% of all purchases (2,652) compared to females at 32% (1,248). Males made more than double the number of purchases. This means that data may not reflect equal shopping patterns between genders.

Gender Shopping Patterns by State

States with the Largest Gender Differences in Purchases

Insights on Gender Differences by State

FigureÂ 14 analyzes cross-gender shopping patterns across the United States, where blue indicates men buying more traditionally feminine items and red shows women buying more masculine items. Only four states show statistically significant differences. In Idaho, where women purchase significantly more masculine items, and in Minnesota, Mississippi, and Georgia where men purchase more feminine items. Ohio displays the strongest blue pattern, while Idaho shows the strongest red. Significant states suggests that cross-gender shopping behaviors are influenced more by state cultural factors and gender norms when it comes to purchasing remains consistent across the country.

Customer Count by Purchase Frequency

Insights on Customer Count by Purchase Frequency

FigureÂ 16 shows that customers are pretty evenly spread across all shopping frequencies ranging from 539 to 584 people for each frequency. The color gradient reveals average review ratings between 3.73 and 3.77, with people who shop every 1-3 months showing slightly higher satisfaction than those on a quarterly schedule. Quarterly shoppers are the least satisfied even though there are a larger number of them suggesting that timing might be an issue. Based on the satisfaction scores, targeting customers who naturally shop every 3 months with subscription offers or special promotions could be a smart move since theyâre already the happiest with their experience.

Conclusions

My analysis reveals three critical insights. Firstly, the 55+ age group generates the highest revenue, with subscription customers contributing more than non-subscribers. Second, Montana, California, and Idaho have the largest number of purchases and 68% of customers are male meaning that the female market is untapped. Third, customer satisfaction varies significantly by purchase frequency, with every-3-month shoppers rating highest (3.77) despite quarterly shoppers representing larger numbers but showing the lowest satisfaction. In addition, medium sizes were the most sold and XL and S were at the same level and maybe those sizes need more options.
